{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:13:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/365"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.04,0.06,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37221"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14407"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of increasing pain in his left leg. He appears confused and is unable to give a clear history. A work colleague reports that two days ago, the patient fell off his tractor and cut his leg against a fence. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 96/62 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 39.4\u00b0C. His left leg is warm, red, and swollen, with blistering surrounding the cut. Examination of the leg causes severe pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 38 x 10x10\u003Csup\u003E9/\u003C/sup\u003EL (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 165 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is immediately started on oxygen, intravenous fluids, and intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperbaric oxygen therapy","Intubation, ventilation and dialysis","CT scan of the left leg","Wound biopsy","Surgical debridement"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of necrotising fasciitis, a rapidly progressive soft tissue infection that requires urgent management. The key features include rapid onset of severe pain, systemic toxicity (fever, tachycardia, hypotension), and characteristic skin changes (erythema, swelling, blistering).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical debridement\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive and most critical step in the management of necrotising fasciitis. Urgent and aggressive debridement of all necrotic tissue is essential to control the spread of infection and reduce mortality. Delayed or inadequate debridement has been associated with increased mortality rates. While initial resuscitation and antibiotic therapy are important, they should not delay surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperbaric oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E has been suggested as an adjunctive treatment for necrotising fasciitis, but its efficacy remains unproven. It should not delay definitive surgical management and is not widely available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation, ventilation and dialysis\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary supportive measures in severe cases of necrotising fasciitis, particularly if the patient develops septic shock or multi-organ failure. However, these are not the definitive treatment and should not take precedence over surgical debridement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the left leg\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in confirming the diagnosis and determining the extent of tissue involvement. However, if necrotising fasciitis is strongly suspected clinically, obtaining imaging should not delay surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E can provide microbiological and histological confirmation of necrotising fasciitis. However, in a patient with high clinical suspicion, waiting for biopsy results before proceeding to surgery could lead to dangerous delays in treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all aspects of management (including resuscitation, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and supportive care) are important in necrotising fasciitis, urgent surgical debridement remains the cornerstone of treatment and should be prioritized to improve patient outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urgent surgical debridement is the definitive management for necrotising fasciitis and should not be delayed.","Necrotising fasciitis presents with rapid progression of symptoms, severe pain, and systemic toxicity.","Initial management of necrotising fasciitis includes resuscitation, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and urgent surgical referral."],"references":["Agarwal L, Yasin A. Necrotising fasciitis: a fatal case of sepsis and a diagnostic challenge \u2013 case report and review of literature. Int J Emerg Med. 2018:11;23. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1186/s12245-018-0183-x","Hakkarainen TW, Kopari NM, Pham TN, Evans HL. Necrotizing soft tissue infections: review and current concepts in treatment, systems of care, and outcomes. Curr Probl Surg. 2014;51(8):344-362. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4199388/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37221"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37221"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T15:00:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T15:01:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"365"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of t